   <abstract>The following treatise is based on content from two separate lecture recitals that were presented from 2021-2022 at Florida State University. The first lecture was given on December 4th, 2021, covered the topic of the purpose of allusion in select works by Mikhail Johnson, Samuel Adams, and Adam O'Dell, and was followed by a performance of the discussed works. On March 28th, 2022, a second lecture will be presented on Liszt's Sonata in B Minor that discusses the Faustian and biblical programs associated with the piece. The first chapter discusses the possibility of humor, creativity, or homage serving as the purpose for alluding to previous composers. Johnson's Wach ya HAYDN!, Adams's Sonatas, and O'Dell's To Aram from Adam (which I had the privilege of commissioning in 2021) are analyzed, with musical elements such as melody, texture, rhythm, form, and quotation being discussed and compared to music written by the connected past composer. By examining these pieces and their associations, the author hopes to stimulate discussion and interest in these composers and their fascinating new works. The second chapter discusses two possible programs for Liszt's Piano Sonata in B Minor. Scholars such as Bertrand Ott propose that the main characters in Goethe's Faust are the inspiration behind the primary musical themes, while others, like Tibor Sz√°sz, advocate for an interpretation of Liszt's musical symbolism from a religious perspective. In comparing and contrasting these two programs, the author hopes to deepen the reader's and listener's appreciation of the work and to give pianists further considerations for interpretation.</abstract>
